The Demonstratio, when found in a formula, immediately follows the appointment of the iudex, and contains the allegationof fact upon which tbe plaintiff bases his claim. It invariably begins with ‘quod' ‘whereas ς’ eg. in Gaius iv. 39 ‘quod Aulus Agerius Numerio Ne· gidio hominem vendidit ;' or · apud Numerium Negidium hominem deposuit! Occasionally the place of the demonstratio is taken bya praescriptio (pro actore), and sometimes even the latter is prefixed to or worked into the former 3 its use is contined to formulae upon actions in which the plaintiff is entitled from the defendant to a number or variety of acts prima facie hanging together, but of which oue only, ⁸ or at least not all, are claimed in the present aetion. By the prae· scriptio, beginning ‘ea res agatur, let the present trial relate exclusively to so and s0,' the plaintiff reserved his right of action upon the other acts, or those subsequently to fall due, which would otherwise have been consumed; it being a presumption of Roman law (capable, however, of being rebutted by the insertion ofa praescriptio in the formula) that when a man instituted an action, it comprised all his claims against the defendant, prospective no less than present, so far at least as they related to the present ground of action, and already had at least a potential existence. Two examples are given by Gaius In the one, a man to whom au annuity is payable, say, every six months, sues for a half year’s instalment, using the praescriptio ‘ea res agatur cuius rei dies fuit 3' in the other, the purchaser of an estate, claiming that it shall be conveyed to him by mancipation, reserves to himself the right of subsequently demanding its mere traditio by a praescriptio in the form ‘ea res agatur de fundo mancipando!

- The Intentio, which follows the Demonstratio if there be one,is the part of the formula ‘qua ector desiderium suurn concludit: in which the plaintiff either affirms the legal right which he claims against the defendant, or else states a fact or facts (in which latter case' there is never a demonstratio) from which the right is to be inferred.
